Here's the xUnit equivalent:

```csharp
// Fixture class replaces [OneTimeSetUp] / [OneTimeTearDown]
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

// Constructor replaces [SetUp]; IDisposable replaces [TearDown]
public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

**Key mappings:**

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` / `[OneTimeTearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` — fixture ctor / `Dispose` |
| `[SetUp]` / `[TearDown]` | Test class constructor / `IDisposable.Dispose` |
| `[TestFixture]` | *(removed — convention-based)* |
| `[Test]` | `[Fact]` |
| `Assert.That(x, Is.Not.Null)` | `Assert.NotNull(x)` |
| `Assert.That(x, Is.EqualTo(y))` | `Assert.Equal(y, x)` |

The `DatabaseFixture` instance is created once and shared across all tests in the class. xUnit injects it via the constructor. If you need to share it across multiple test classes, use `ICollectionFixture<T>` instead.
